{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/machine-learning-for-stock-clustering-using-k-means-algorithm-126bc1ace4e1", "time": 1682994599.8311832, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/machine-learning-for-stock-clustering-using-k-means-algorithm-126bc1ace4e1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Machine Learning for Stock Clustering using K-Means Algorithm | by Saad Ahmed | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Machine Learning for Stock Clustering using K-Means Algorithm", "description": "Diversification is a key step for constructing portfolios but true diversification is not possible as investing in each company requires a lot of capital. Apart from this, not all companies are worth\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.almeezangroup.com/investor-education/shariah-methodology/", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 3}], "all_paragraphs": ["Diversification is a key step for constructing portfolios but true diversification is not possible as investing in each company requires a lot of capital. Apart from this, not all companies are worth investing in and that may be because they are highly illiquid.", "So now what you want to do is come up with an effective strategy where you pick only those stocks that behave differently. This will help in mitigating the risk and one way of doing it is to pick stocks from different sectors but a more data-driven solution can be to apply K-Means clustering algorithm on stock data to identify different clusters of stocks.", "In the following post, I will give an example of applying the K-Means algorithm using Python.", "First, we need our data in an organized structure. For this task, I am going to use a list of Shariah Compliant stocks as listed here. The list has been updated so my selection of companies may be a bit different.", "The following code block loads the data from the computer and structures it according to our needs", "Now before fitting the model to our data we need to decide the number of clusters we want our data to be divided into. Deciding this number can be tricky therefore we will use the \u201cElbow Method\u201d to calculate the SSE(Sum Squared error) for a range of different clusters. We will then plot the number of clusters on the x-axis and the SSE on the y-axis.", "The figure below gives us an indication that 5 clusters are a good number here as we don't want the n_clusters to be too big and as the error rate decrease slows down after 5, therefore, I think its a justified selection.", "So now we are going to fit the K-Means model again to our dataset with n_clusters = 5 and plot the results.", "Just like any other data science problem, we have an outlier in our data and we need to remove it by identifying which company it is. The following code does the same.", "After removing we now re-do the process of fitting the model and plotting it.", "What's left now for us to do is just get the cluster number of each company in our data set so that we can differentiate between companies while constructing a diversified portfolio.", "I have focused more on the implementation of the algorithm in python instead of explaining the theory. I hope this article has proved to be useful for you. If you have any questions or found any technical mistake do let me know in the comments section below.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F126bc1ace4e1&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fmachine-learning-for-stock-clustering-using-k-means-algorithm-126bc1ace4e1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/si